A better year for migrants?
DUBLIN – Two major lessons emerge from the migration crisis in the Mediterranean.
First, Europe and the international community apply a cruelly ill-suited system for the protection of the most vulnerable migrants.
Secondly, in the face of the inefficiency of this system, populist actors continuously exploit fears in order to gain political support, undermining liberal and tolerant societies whose construction required some 70 years of determined efforts.
This is why it is essential to undertake a genuinely active initiative at the European and global levels this year.
Next September, United Nations Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon will convene an extraordinary summit aimed at establishing a robust global protection system for the most vulnerable migrants and refugees.
Let's hope that states will be ready to commit in a concrete and lasting manner.
This necessary commitment was cruelly lacking during the year 2015.
Indeed, the international community would have been able to limit the severity of last year's crisis if it had provided even the most minimal support to the frontline countries—Turkey, Lebanon, and Jordan—which together host no fewer than four million refugees.
With only about 10 billion euros, these countries would have been better able to house, feed, and provide education to the refugees, thus reducing the temptation to flee to Europe.
This failure could cost Germany alone up to 21 billion euros each year in the coming years.
But the financial implications of the crisis are nothing compared to its human and political costs.
More than a million people risked their lives last year by crossing the Mediterranean, subsequently enduring an exhausting journey through the Balkans.
Close to 4,000 migrants lost their lives there, while many European countries turned their backs on the survivors by refusing to offer them refuge.
The most cynical politicians have mercilessly exploited citizens' fears by promoting a hateful nationalist vision that either ignores or distorts the life experiences of migrants.
In the United States, for example, not one of the 780,000 refugees resettled since September 11, 2001, has been found guilty of any terrorist activity.
At the same time, immigrants generally pay more in taxes than they receive in social benefits.
And yet, extremist parties are dangerously flirting with seizing political power in certain European countries, and are currently gaining support even within formerly liberal strongholds.
Anti-immigration parties are already in power in Hungary and Poland.
Their success, meanwhile, leads traditional parties to promote a policy hostile to immigration as well.
This situation has seriously undermined European cooperation.
The EU program aimed at dealing with the million refugees who arrived on its shores has only managed to "relocate" 190 of them.
Border controls in six countries belonging to the Schengen area have been reinstated, at least temporarily.
In the eyes of the rest of the world, the EU appears today nationalist and incompetent.
Of course, resolving this crisis concerns not only Europe; responsibility cannot be defined merely by geographical proximity.
In any case, the EU is undoubtedly facing today a threat to its own existence, which it can overcome only by firmly demonstrating the solidarity and international leadership it is capable of.
This is why it is up to the member states to take the initiative by proposing solutions.
The most urgent priority is to establish legal and safe pathways for refugees to reach Europe.
It is not about asserting that every migrant in difficulty must be welcomed.
It nonetheless falls to the EU to be more systematically generous in determining the number of refugees to welcome and to employ orderly mechanisms aimed at facilitating their entry.
Such a system would allow for the protection of migrants while safeguarding Europe (through the possibility of fully examining applications).
Beyond an approach aimed at deterring asylum seekers from risking their lives by crossing the Mediterranean, such a strategy would also allow projecting an image of solidarity towards frontline countries, which continue to host the majority of refugees.
Equally important, this approach would encourage the rest of the international community to contribute to the efforts.
This leads us to the second priority of 2016: building a solid global system for the protection of vulnerable refugees and migrants.
This goal will first require that more countries agree to host refugees.
In recent years, the United Nations Refugee Agency has only managed to resettle less than 75,000 of the approximately 20 million annual refugees.
Millions of them end up in a prolonged migration situation, estimated to last an average of 25 years, trapped in a kind of purgatory and uncertain about the day of a possible return home.
In 2016, it is necessary for developed countries to agree to host, each year, a cumulative number of nearly one million refugees, either through their resettlement or by granting them humanitarian, student, professional, or other visas.
Since Canada has stated that it would alone welcome 50,000 Syrian refugees this year, this is clearly an achievable goal.
At the same time, the international community will need to support the integration of refugees into major host countries such as Turkey, Kenya, Lebanon, and Jordan.
As things stand today, these countries only receive a fraction of the $3,000 to $5,000 annually needed per refugee for housing, food, care, education, and vocational training during the first years of settlement.
And these figures do not take into account the necessary cost of constructing or upgrading infrastructure.
In Lebanon, for example, water supply systems are suffering from the pressure caused by the massive arrival of refugees.
In exchange for funding, these host countries could commit to fully integrating refugees into their schools, labor markets, and civic institutions.
But effective integration of migrants will only be possible if European countries and others get rid of their prejudices regarding migrants.
If these groups continue to be seen as a burden, or even as a threat to security, reactionary political forces will keep gaining ground, by depriving newcomers of opportunities and by turning fear into a self-fulfilling prophecy.
On the other hand, if host countries manage to integrate migrants enthusiastically, everyone will benefit—including these countries (notably through remittances).
Last month, in Paris, the international community proved that it was capable of subordinating its national interests to a broader global objective: the fight against climate change.
In 2016, a similar effort is needed to build a better protection system for migrants.
This is a matter of life or death for some 20 million refugees, for several million other vulnerable migrants – as well as a profound test of the civic health of democratic societies around the world.
